@Node "Preferences window" "sig.guide/Preferences window"
@Next "Options"
@Prev "Keys-Menus"
@Toc "Main"

Preferences window
******************

   All the settings here reflect the @{"Options" Link "Options"} via Toolstypes or CLI. See
the descriptions there for their meaning.

   A few things about the Prefs-Window. When klicking on the gadgets
right next to the Screen-mode text-Gadgets, you get a screen-mode
requester.  The Gadget on the left of the Source-Screen-Mode is for the
(not) visibility of the Picture-Screen.

   When clicking on the gadget labeled "Preview" next to the
Pattern-dimension area, a window will open, and you get to see the
pattern. The viewing is done (how could it be else?) via datatype. This
way, it can be (and is) done asynchronously. So if you load e.g. a GIF
or even a JPEG, it can take a while before it is visible. You can do
everything else what you want.

   The preview window is an AppWindow. This means (if you have WBPREFS
set) you can move your patterns on it, and they will be used, as if you
clicked on the @{i}load pattern@{ui} button, right of the display of the
pattern-file-name.

   The save-Gadget saves the current confirguration to
@{b}ENV:SIRDS_GEN.prefs@{ub} & @{b}ENVARC:SIRDS_GEN.prefs@{ub}. You can edit the options
there if you like; they're saved as ASCII. If used is clicked, the
options are saved only to @{b}ENV:SIRDS_GEN.prefs@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Options" "sig.guide/Options"
@Next "Address"
@Prev "Preferences window"
@Toc "Main"

Options
*******

   Here are the Options for configuring the Program.
   - you can use them as ToolTypes (e.g. @{b}HIDDEN@{ub})

   - if you want to have an option disabled, add @{b}NO@{ub} in front of it. (e.g
     @{b}NOHIDDEN@{ub})

   - use them as CLI-Argument (e.g. @{b}SIRDS_GEN SIRDS_SCREEN="PAL:HighRes
     Interlace" EYEPOS BOTTOM NOBEEP@{ub})

   - When starting from CLI, you can specify an options-file to load.
     It is specified with a @{i} @@{ui} followed by a filename. @{i}Note: The @{i} @@{ui} has
     to be the first symbol in the commandline@{ui}. Everything which
     follows will be parsed too.  (example: @{b}SIRDS_GEN
     @ENV:SIRDS_GEN.prefs FILE cave.pic INVERSE@{ub}) will load the prefs
     twice).  If the file contains spaces, you can surround the file
     with quotes: @{b}SIRDS_GEN @"t:SIG file"@{ub}

   - or click on the corresponding gadget in the Prefs window

   Options marked with @{i}(Startup only)@{ui} are only setable on startup (as
CLI-option or Tooltype). If you want to set them for default, start the
program with the appropiate options, enter the prefs-window and click
on save, or you can edit the prefs-file, and add the option there.


 @{" [NO]BEEP " Link "[NO]BEEP"}         Display a beep after drawing
 @{" [NO]CAMG_MASK " Link "[NO]CAMG_MASK"}    Save IFF with modified CAMG_MASK
 @{" [NO]COLORS " Link "[NO]COLORS"}       Sort colors of loaded pic before drawing
 @{" DARKNESS " Link "DARKNESS"}         Set the percentage of black pixels for SIRDS
 @{" EYEPOS " Link "EYEPOS"}           define where the @{i}eyes@{ui} should be placed
 @{" EYEWIDTH " Link "EYEWIDTH"}         define the width of the eyes
 @{" FILE " Link "FILE"}             specify the picture to be loaded as source @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" FUNCTION " Link "FUNCTION"}         specify the function to be drawn @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" [NO]HIDDEN " Link "[NO]HIDDEN"}       use HIDDEN mode
 @{" [NO]INVERSE " Link "[NO]INVERSE"}      create inverse-SIRDS
 @{" MINX-MAXX " Link "MINX-MAXX"}        define the x-dimension of the function
 @{" MINY-MAXY " Link "MINY-MAXY"}        define the y-dimension of the function
 @{" MINZ-MAXZ " Link "MINZ-MAXZ"}        define the z-dimension of the function
 @{" MIX " Link "MIX"}              mix function & picture
 @{" PATTERN " Link "PATTERN"}          choose the pattern for SIS
 @{" PAT_MODE " Link "PAT_MODE"}         choose the pattern mode
 @{" [NO]PICOSAVE " Link "[NO]PICOSAVE"}     save IFFs on Piccolo @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" PIC_DEPTH " Link "PIC_DEPTH"}        set the virtual depth of the SIRDS
 @{" [NO]PREFS_FIRST " Link "[NO]PREFS_FIRST"}  show the preferences before drawing @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" RASTER " Link "RASTER"}           set the raster for a function
 @{" SAVEFILE " Link "SAVEFILE"}         set the file to be saved @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" SAVEGIFFILE " Link "SAVEGIFFILE"}      set the GIF-file to be saved @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" SEED " Link "SEED"}             set the initial seed for SIRDS @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}
 @{" [NO]SHOW_SRC " Link "[NO]SHOW_SRC"}     view the source picture
 @{" SIRDS_SCREEN " Link "SIRDS_SCREEN"}     set the display-mode for the SIRDS
 @{" SIRDS_HEIGHT " Link "SIRDS_HEIGHT"}     set the height for the SIRDS
 @{" SIRDS_WIDTH " Link "SIRDS_WIDTH"}      set the width for the SIRDS
 @{" SRC_SCREEN " Link "SRC_SCREEN"}       set the mode for the source-picture
 @{" [NO]WBPREFS " Link "[NO]WBPREFS"}      show Preferences on the workbench @{i}(Startup only)@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "FUNCTION" "sig.guide/FUNCTION"
@Next "[NO]HIDDEN"
@Prev "FILE"
@Toc "Options"

FUNCTION
========

   Starting with version 2.7, you are able to plot 3-dimensional
function with a SIRDS-algorithm. Really great if you can't think of
what a function will look like. The way you see it, is straight from
top down to the function. You can set all ranges of the function as you
desire.

The complete EBNF-syntax of the function-plotter is:
     func := 'z' '=' expr.
     expr := CmpOp ('<'|'>'|'<='|'>='|'='|'<>') CmpOp.
     CmpOp := term {('+'|'-') term}.
     term := factor {('*'|'/'|'%'|'div'|'mod') factor}.
     factor := value {('^'|'**') value}.
     value := ['+'|'-'] number | 'x' | 'y' | '(' expr ')'.
     value := ('abs'|'asin'|'acos'|'atan'|'cos'|'cosh'|'exp'|'log') '(' expr ')'.
     value := ('log10'|'sin'|'sinh'|'sqrt'|'tan'|'tanh') '(' expr ')'.
     value := 'if' '(' expr ',' expr ',' expr ')'.
     value := ('rad'|'radius') '(' expr ',' expr ')'.
     value := 'dist' '(' expr ',' expr ',' expr ',' expr ')'.

   The function must contain a variable "z" at the beginning followed
by a "=".  The rest must be a valid function, else an error will occure.

The function parser understands the standard amount of functions:

         "*"         "abs"          "cosh"
         "/"         "acos"         "sinh"
         "+"         "asin"         "tanh"
         "-"         "atan"         "exp"
         "^"         "cos"          "log"
         "**"        "sin"          "log10"
         "()"        "tan"          "sqrt"

non standard:

     "div"    -  div-operator           5.7 div 0.5 (-> 11)
     "mod"    -  modulo                 5.7 mod 0.5 (-> 0.2)
     "%"      -  same as modulo
     "if"     -  if clause (see below)
     "<", ">", "=", "<=", ">=", "<>" - boolean operators (see below)
     "radius" - radius(x,y) = dist(x, y, 0, 0)
     "rad"    - same as radius
     "dist"   - distance of 2 points. syntax: dist(expr, expr, expr, expr)
                                      dist(2,4,6,7) -> (2,4) to (6,7) -> 5

Numbers can be written as you like. e.g the following will be accepted:
     1.2e-3
     .67
     -23.6

   Another feature of the parser is, that a minus in front of a term,
will be treated, as if there stands @{b}-1*term@{ub}. e.g if you want to enter a
term like @{b}z=-1*sin(x)@{ub} you could just enter @{b}z=-sin(x)@{ub}. Therefore this
construction is valid too: @{b}z=2-x@{ub} which would result in @{b}z=2-(-1*x)@{ub}

   Of course @{b}*@{ub} and @{b}/@{ub} have a higher priority than @{b}+@{ub} and @{b}-@{ub}. And @{b}^@{ub} or @{b}**@{ub}
have a higher priority than @{b}*@{ub} and @{b}/@{ub}. So there is no need to use braces
all the time, like @{b}2+3*x@{ub}.

   There doesn't exist any limit for the amount of braces. The only
limitation is the length of 256 bytes for the whole function, which
should be enough.

   The boolean functions return a value of (1.0) for true and (0.0) for
false.  e.g. @{b}z=(x<0)*x@{ub} would result in:
     x<0  : z=x
     x>=0 : z=0

   don't forget the braces; boolean expressions have the lowest
priority.  e.g @{b}z=x<0*x@{ub} would be the same as @{b}z=x<(0*x)@{ub} which is @{b}z=x<0@{ub}

   The if-clause syntax is: @{b}if (expr, true-expr, false-expr)@{ub} The
expression is tested, against 0.0. If it's not 0.0 then the expr is
true, and the true expression is calculated, otherwise the
false-expression will be used.  It is useful, to use the boolean
expression for the first expression.

now a few examples:
     z=if(x>0, 1, -1)
    This would result in 1 if x>0, and -1 when x<=0.

lets simulate the signum function:
     x>0: z=1
     x=0: z=0
     x<0: z=-1
    just do something like @{b}z=if(x > 0, 1, if (x=0, 0, -1))@{ub} but you can
do it faster if you type @{b}z=(x>0)-(x<0)@{ub}

A great thing to do with the @{b}dist()@{ub}-function is the drawing of
interfering sine-curves. If you draw one starting from (0/0), then you
would do @{b}z=cos(radius(x,y))@{ub} which will result in a circular sine-curve,
starting at the origin, just if you throw a stone in the lake, and
watch the waves.  You can set any middle point with the
@{b}dist()@{ub}-function. i.e.  @{b}z=cos(dist(x,y,0,3))@{ub} would start in (0/3).
To overlap these two, just add them together. Multiplication is funny
too.

   As I often use the @{b}rad()@{ub}-function, there exists a shortcut @{b}r@{ub} for
@{b}rad(x,y)@{ub}. You can simply type @{b}z=sin(r)@{ub} to get a circular sine-wave.

here is an example of three points:
     z = cos(radius(x,y)) * cos(dist(x,y,0,5)) * cos(dist(x,y,5,5))
     range: xmin = -11, xmax = 13
            ymin =  -8, ymax = 10
            zmin =  -1, zmax = 1

There exists a default function, which is @{b}z=-0.3*(x*x+y*y)+2@{ub}


@EndNode

@Node "MINX-MAXX" "sig.guide/MINX-MAXX"
@Next "MINY-MAXY"
@Prev "[NO]INVERSE"
@Toc "Options"

MINX/MAXX
=========

   MINX and MAXX define the x-range of the function to be plotted.
Default is from -6 to 6.  !


@EndNode

@Node "MINY-MAXY" "sig.guide/MINY-MAXY"
@Next "MINZ-MAXZ"
@Prev "MINX-MAXX"
@Toc "Options"

MINY/MAXY
=========

MINY and MAXY define the y-range of the function to be plotted.
Default is from -6 to 6.  !


@EndNode

@Node "MINZ-MAXZ" "sig.guide/MINZ-MAXZ"
@Next "MIX"
@Prev "MINY-MAXY"
@Toc "Options"

MINZ/MAXZ
=========

MINZ and MAXZ define the z-range of the function to be plotted.
Default is from -2 to 2.  !


@EndNode

@Node "DARKNESS" "sig.guide/DARKNESS"
@Next "EYEPOS"
@Prev "[NO]COLORS"
@Toc "Options"

DARKNESS
========

Set the percentage of dark pixels, when drawing a @{i}SIRDS@{ui}. 0 means all
white 100 means all dark. Note: when using 50, the program is slightly
faster.  ! @{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 50


@EndNode

@Node "SEED" "sig.guide/SEED"
@Next "[NO]SHOW_SRC"
@Prev "SAVEGIFFILE"
@Toc "Options"

SEED
====

Set the initial seed for a @{i}SIRDS@{ui}. If you pass 0, then the timer will be
used for the seed -> every time another @{i}SIRDS@{ui}.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 0


@EndNode

@Node "SAVEFILE" "sig.guide/SAVEFILE"
@Next "SAVEGIFFILE"
@Prev "RASTER"
@Toc "Options"

SAVEFILE
========

   When using this option, you have to pass a filename, which the @{i}SIRDS@{ui}
will be saved to. You can only save IFF-files this way. The picture is
saved immediately after drawing, and the program then terminates.
Useful for making a bunch of pictures, e.g. for an animation.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: <none>


@EndNode

@Node "SRC_SCREEN" "sig.guide/SRC_SCREEN"
@Next "[NO]WBPREFS"
@Prev "SIRDS_WIDTH"
@Toc "Options"

SRC_SCREEN
==========

   Screenmode for the Pic-Screen. If no valid Screenmode is found,
@{i}BestModeID()@{ui} is used for getting the right mode.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: PAL:LowRes


@EndNode

@Node "SIRDS_SCREEN" "sig.guide/SIRDS_SCREEN"
@Next "SIRDS_HEIGHT"
@Prev "[NO]SHOW_SRC"
@Toc "Options"

SIRDS_SCREEN
============

   Screenmode for the SIRDS-Screen.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: NTSC:HighRes Interlace


@EndNode

@Node "SIRDS_WIDTH" "sig.guide/SIRDS_WIDTH"
@Next "SRC_SCREEN"
@Prev "SIRDS_HEIGHT"
@Toc "Options"

SIRDS_WIDTH
===========

   Width of the SIRDS-Screen. If zero, the STANDARD Overscan width of
the screenmode will be used. Try bigger value than StdOscan. The
Autoscrolling looks really nice.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 0


@EndNode

@Node "SIRDS_HEIGHT" "sig.guide/SIRDS_HEIGHT"
@Next "SIRDS_WIDTH"
@Prev "SIRDS_SCREEN"
@Toc "Options"

SIRDS_HEIGHT
============

   Height of the SIRDS-Screen. If zero, the STANDARD Overscan height of
the screenmode will be used.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 0


@EndNode

@Node "EYEPOS" "sig.guide/EYEPOS"
@Next "EYEWIDTH"
@Prev "DARKNESS"
@Toc "Options"

EYEPOS
======

   Position of the Eyes:
@{b}TOP@{ub}
     At the Top (default)

@{b}MID@{ub}
     in the Mid of the Screen (if you like it...)

@{b}BOTTOM@{ub}
     at the bottom

@{b}NONE@{ub}
     No Eyes (for those you dont like it at all)

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: none


@EndNode

@Node "EYEWIDTH" "sig.guide/EYEWIDTH"
@Next "FILE"
@Prev "EYEPOS"
@Toc "Options"

EYEWIDTH
========

   The space between the eyes. If you specify "0", the space will be
adjusted to the screenmode: @{b}EYEWIDTH = OSCAN_STANDARD / 10@{ub}.  Actually
@{b}EYEWIDTH@{ub} is the number of pixels per inch. You can use this option if
you want to calculate a @{i}SIRDS@{ui} for another Media, e.g. for printing.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 0


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]HIDDEN" "sig.guide/[NO]HIDDEN"
@Next "[NO]INVERSE"
@Prev "FUNCTION"
@Toc "Options"

HIDDEN
======

   If set, an algorithm for removing hidden layers is used.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: OFF


@EndNode

@Node "PIC_DEPTH" "sig.guide/PIC_DEPTH"
@Next "[NO]PREFS_FIRST"
@Prev "[NO]PICOSAVE"
@Toc "Options"

PIC_DEPTH
=========

   The virtual depth of the @{i}SIRDS@{ui}. It is calculation is the following:
visible_depth = @{b}20 / PIC_DEPTH * max_visible_depth@{ub}. Due to this formula
PIC_DEPTH has to be >=20.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 55


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]BEEP" "sig.guide/[NO]BEEP"
@Next "[NO]CAMG_MASK"
@Toc "Options"

BEEP
====

   If TRUE, a @{i}DisplayBeep(0)@{ui} is generated after each calculation, to
indicate a picture is finished. Some people find this nerving, right
Jens?

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: TRUE


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]CAMG_MASK" "sig.guide/[NO]CAMG_MASK"
@Next "[NO]COLORS"
@Prev "[NO]BEEP"
@Toc "Options"

CAMG_MASK
=========

   When saving as ILBM, some (in fact one) want to mask the screenmode
in the CAMG-chunk to apply a default-monitor. If this flag is true, the
screen-mode will be masked with @{b}INTERLACE | HIRES_KEY@{ub}.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: FALSE


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]INVERSE" "sig.guide/[NO]INVERSE"
@Next "MINX-MAXX"
@Prev "[NO]HIDDEN"
@Toc "Options"

INVERSE
=======

   If set, the vitual depth of the @{i}SIRDS@{ui} will be reversed: The highest
area will be the lowest, and vice versa. Useful for peole who cross
their view before the picture for viewing @{i}SIRDS@{ui}.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: FALSE


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]COLORS" "sig.guide/[NO]COLORS"
@Next "DARKNESS"
@Prev "[NO]CAMG_MASK"
@Toc "Options"

COLORS
======

   If set, the colors are sorted. So the highest color will be the
front-most position in the @{i}SIRDS@{ui}. The colors are sorted in the
following way: r-Val + g-Val + b-Val, and the sorted.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: FALSE


@EndNode

@Node "FILE" "sig.guide/FILE"
@Next "FUNCTION"
@Prev "EYEWIDTH"
@Toc "Options"

FILE
====

   Here you can specify a file for loading. If none specified, you will
be asked for one.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: <none>


@EndNode

@Node "PATTERN" "sig.guide/PATTERN"
@Next "PAT_MODE"
@Prev "MIX"
@Toc "Options"

PATTERN
=======

   requires a File, which will be used as pattern for @{i}SIS@{ui}. The loading
is done via datatypes, so you can use any format you like. The SIS-mode
is automatically activated, when this options is specified.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: <none>


@EndNode

@Node "PAT_MODE" "sig.guide/PAT_MODE"
@Next "[NO]PICOSAVE"
@Prev "PATTERN"
@Toc "Options"

PAT_MODE
========

   4 different Pattern-modes are possible:
  1. The Pattern will be displayed normally on the left, and adjusted
     to the right

  2. The Pattern will be displayed normally in the mid, and adjusted to
     both sides

  3. The Pattern will be displayed normally on the right, and adjusted
     to the left

  4. The Pattern is scaled to the farest point on each line, and
     centered. This is the slowest mode, but the best one. (only
     available with keyfile)

   If you pass a wrong value, a @{i}SIRDS@{ui} will be generated.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 2


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]SHOW_SRC" "sig.guide/[NO]SHOW_SRC"
@Next "SIRDS_SCREEN"
@Prev "SEED"
@Toc "Options"

SHOW_SRC
========

   If OFF, no screen for the source-picture will be opened. Just to
save a little Chip-Mem for bigger @{i}SIRDSs@{ui}.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: ON


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]WBPREFS" "sig.guide/[NO]WBPREFS"
@Prev "SRC_SCREEN"
@Toc "Options"

WBPREFS
=======

   If set, the Prefs-Window will open on the default PubScreen..
Otherwise it will open on the current screen.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: TRUE


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]PREFS_FIRST" "sig.guide/[NO]PREFS_FIRST"
@Next "RASTER"
@Prev "PIC_DEPTH"
@Toc "Options"

PREFS_FIRST
===========

   When set to on, The Prefs-Window will show before the @{i}SIRDS@{ui} will be
drawn. This way, you can select a new screenmode first, if you like.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: ON


@EndNode

@Node "RASTER" "sig.guide/RASTER"
@Next "SAVEFILE"
@Prev "[NO]PREFS_FIRST"
@Toc "Options"

RASTER
======

   This option works in conjunktion with the function-plotter. You can
speed up the drawing, if you increase the raster. Setting @{b}RASTER@{ub} to 1
will plot every pixel, and is really slow. A @{b}RASTER@{ub} of 2 will draw a
square of 4 Pixels which have the same value, and so on. Useful, when
you want to see what a function will look like.  Try using a high
value, such as 50. Looks nice too.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: 3


@EndNode

@Node "SAVEGIFFILE" "sig.guide/SAVEGIFFILE"
@Next "SEED"
@Prev "SAVEFILE"
@Toc "Options"

SAVEGIFFILE
===========

   CLI-option only. You have to specify a file, which the GIF-file will
be saved to. The difference to @{b}SAVEFILE@{ub} is:
  a. The file beeing saved is a GIF-file.

  b. The @{i}SIRDS@{ui} is not shown!
        You have to specify @{"SIRDS_WIDTH" Link "SIRDS_WIDTH"} & @{"SIRDS_HEIGHT" Link "SIRDS_HEIGHT"}, but they can be
any value.  So you can generate @{i}huge@{ui} pictures with this option, without
having to worry about memory.  The only limitations are 256 colors, and
a width < 65536, but that's the limitation of the GIF-format.  After
drawing, the program will end.


@EndNode

@Node "[NO]PICOSAVE" "sig.guide/[NO]PICOSAVE"
@Next "PIC_DEPTH"
@Prev "PAT_MODE"
@Toc "Options"

PICOSAVE
========

   Due to the fact that saving iff-pictures didn't work on a
Piccolo-Gfx-card, this option activates a small workaround: The Bitmap
of the picture is copied to a temporary Bitmap first, which is saved
then. I advise you to not set it if not necessary, due to extra memory
usage when saving.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: OFF


@EndNode

@Node "MIX" "sig.guide/MIX"
@Next "PATTERN"
@Prev "MINZ-MAXZ"
@Toc "Options"

MIX
===

   This Options enables the mix of a picture with a formula. To get
things right, you need to know, that all heights are scaled to an area
between 0 and 1. 0 is the back plane and 1 is the front-most plane.

   There are 4 different ways to mix:

@{b}ADD@{ub}
     This calculates the arithmetic mid of the function an the formula.
     i.e.  (pic_height + fml_height) / 2

@{b}MUL@{ub}
     Multiplication of picture and formula. Useful if you want to cut
     out something of a formula. Just take a 2-color picture.

@{b}MAX@{ub}
     takes the highest area's of picture or formula. You can have a
     Text fly above a sine wave for example.

@{b}MIN@{ub}
     takes the minimum of picture and formula. Just for completeness.

@{b}none@{ub}
     well, this is the default and doesn't mix the two.

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub}: none


@EndNode

